Note: ============================================================================
Note: WINDOWS-SYNTHESIZED UNIX SYSCALL NUMBER SENTINELS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher requires 27 SYS_* nullary procs
that return the Unix-style syscall number for each operation. On
Windows there is no concept of a "Unix syscall number" — kernel
operations are reached through the Win32 API by symbol name, not via
a numeric index in a syscall table.

Per the P2-B design doc (line 323): "windows_x86_64_SYS_READ() returns
0 — the syscall number is meaningless on Windows; we return a sentinel
that the user-code never uses because the Windows syscall_read wrapper
bypasses the number." The same principle applies to windows_arm64.

Synthesis policy: each SYS_* proc returns -1 as a sentinel meaning
"syscall numbers are not applicable on Windows; use the matching
Win32 API wrapper instead." This differs from the design doc's
example (which used 0) because:

1. The Win32 API wrappers (`api_create_file`, `api_read_file`, etc.)
   exist as direct entry points; the high-level `syscall_*` wrappers
   in this file already route through `api_*` calls, NOT through the
   numeric `SYS_*` indirection.
2. The sentinel -1 makes accidental misuse loud: if any caller ever
   passes `SYS_READ()` into a `syscall_3()` call on Windows, the
   resulting syscall number -1 is rejected by every conceivable
   kernel32 entry, producing an immediate failure.
3. The value 0 happens to be a valid kernel32 import-thunk address
   (NULL pointer dereference) which could silently crash; -1 has no
   such collision.

Per @Reasoning on api_* additions above: Windows callers should route
through the explicit api_* surface (api_read_file, api_write_file,
api_create_file, etc.). The SYS_* sentinels exist only to satisfy the
dispatcher's compile-time bare-name link graph (P2-B Gate C / Gate D
closure).

The 27 names match exactly the dispatcher's published SYS_* surface:
SYS_BRK, SYS_CHDIR, SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME, SYS_CLOSE, SYS_CREAT, SYS_EXIT,
SYS_EXIT_GROUP, SYS_FSTAT, SYS_GETCWD, SYS_GETEGID, SYS_GETEUID,
SYS_GETGID, SYS_GETPID, SYS_GETPPID, SYS_GETUID, SYS_LSEEK,
SYS_LSTAT, SYS_MKDIR, SYS_MMAP, SYS_MUNMAP, SYS_OPEN, SYS_READ,
SYS_RMDIR, SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY, SYS_STAT, SYS_UNLINK, SYS_WRITE.

Mapping from SYS_* to the Win32 path that the matching syscall_*
wrapper routes through (informational; the SYS_* number itself is
never used on Windows):

| SYS_*                  | Win32 API path                            |
|------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| SYS_READ               | ReadFile (api_read_file)                  |
| SYS_WRITE              | WriteFile (api_write_file)                |
| SYS_OPEN, SYS_CREAT    | CreateFileW (api_create_file)             |
| SYS_CLOSE              | CloseHandle (api_close_handle)            |
| SYS_LSEEK              | SetFilePointerEx (future FFI)             |
| SYS_STAT, SYS_LSTAT,
  SYS_FSTAT              | GetFileInformationByHandle (future FFI)   |
| SYS_MKDIR              | CreateDirectoryW (api_create_directory)   |
| SYS_RMDIR              | RemoveDirectoryW (api_remove_directory)   |
| SYS_UNLINK             | DeleteFileW (api_delete_file)             |
| SYS_CHDIR              | SetCurrentDirectoryW (future FFI)         |
| SYS_GETCWD             | GetCurrentDirectoryW (future FFI)         |
| SYS_MMAP, SYS_MUNMAP   | VirtualAlloc/VirtualFree (api_virtual_*)  |
| SYS_BRK                | (no equivalent; use VirtualAlloc)         |
| SYS_EXIT, SYS_EXIT_GROUP | TerminateProcess (api_terminate_process) |
| SYS_GETPID             | GetCurrentProcessId (api_get_current_process_id) |
| SYS_GETPPID            | (NT-only via NtQueryInformationProcess)   |
| SYS_GETUID, GETGID,
  GETEUID, GETEGID       | GetTokenInformation (future FFI)          |
| SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME      | QueryPerformanceCounter (api_query_*)     |
| SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY  | GetProcessAffinityMask (future FFI)       |

Sources: Microsoft Learn Win32 API reference (per-API page cited
above); P2-B design doc section "Special case: Windows synthesizes
Unix-style API" (line 317-325).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each SYS_* proc is a nullary Process returning -1. The dispatcher
resolves `SYS_READ from Syscall` to this proc on windows_arm64
targets via the bare-name pattern in force during Wave 1.

The bodies are intentionally minimal (single Return -1) because no
useful computation can be performed: the syscall-number concept does
not exist on Windows. Compiler inlining at the call site eliminates
the call overhead and the unused-value optimisation will fold away
the call entirely if the result is not consumed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single mov-immediate / return. Compiler inlines and folds. Zero
runtime cost. Callers should NOT use SYS_* values on Windows; the
correct path is the Win32-native api_* wrapper (api_read_file etc.).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning -1 has no security state. The sentinel value is chosen
specifically to fail loudly if accidentally fed into a syscall-by-
number dispatcher (no kernel32 thunk exists at address -1, so the
call crashes immediately rather than silently mis-dispatching).

This is a defence-in-depth measure: if a caller bug accidentally
routes a SYS_* value to syscall_N on Windows, the failure mode is
immediate-and-visible rather than silent-and-corrupting.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_READ" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_read_file (ReadFile); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_write_file (WriteFile); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_OPEN" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_create_file (CreateFileW); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_CLOSE" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_close_handle (CloseHandle); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_create_file with CREATE_ALWAYS; N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_STAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses GetFileInformationByHandle (future FFI); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_LSTAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows has no lstat (no symlink semantics); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_FSTAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses GetFileInformationByHandle (future FFI); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_LSEEK" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses SetFilePointerEx (future FFI); N/A
End Process

